# Fleet Details by Rego

1. Introduction 

1. Welcome to the family! 

OzHarvest is Australia’s leading food rescue organisation with a driving purpose to Nourish Our Country. Founded by Ronni Kahn in 2004, it began with a simple concept to rescue good food that would otherwise go to waste and deliver it to people in need. 

Each week OzHarvest rescues over 180 tonnes of quality surplus food from more than 3,000 food donors including supermarkets, restaurants, cafes, hotels, airports and food outlets and delivers directly to more than 1300 charitable agencies. 

To create positive change for vulnerable people, OzHarvest runs education programs NEST and Nourish to enhance life skills, increase connectedness and improve health, nutrition and sustainable living, and recently opened Australia’s first rescued food supermarket – The OzHarvest Market – based on a ‘take what you need, give if you can’ philosophy, making rescued food available to all, especially those in need. 

Every $1 donated allows OzHarvest to deliver two meals to people in need.  

This handbook will provide useful information on the organisation, Food Rescue, use of OzHarvest vehicles, and your role as an OzHarvest Driver.  

1.2 What we do at OzHarvest 

 OzHarvest has four pillars that will direct the work that we do:  

Rescue - Eliminating hunger and food waste through the redistribution of quality surplus food underpins everything we do.  Our framework for food rescue now operates from eight cities and through regional communities across Australia, enabling OzHarvest to save millions of kilos of good food from landfill.   

Educate - Education about healthy eating, nutrition, preventing food waste and sustainability is central to our purpose, along with protecting and improving the environment through our actions. Our education programs are designed to increase community connectedness, improve self-worth and confidence and deliver the important food waste and sustainability message.  

Engage - Community engagement is the heartbeat of OzHarvest and continues to grow every day through our devoted team of like-minded partners and our ever-growing ‘yellow army’ of volunteers. There is no better way to experience how we nourish our country than rolling up your sleeves and getting involved.  

Innovate - OzHarvest is constantly looking for new ways and innovative solutions to combat food waste and hunger and use technology to mobilise everyday Australians to take meaningful action. We are proud of the unique for-impact, OzHarvest food rescue model which is being introduced to other countries across the globe. 

We strongly encourage all our new family members to take some time and visit [www.ozharvest.org](http://www.ozharvest.org/) to inform themselves about the different ways OzHarvest impacts the community and to please reach out to program coordinators and other staff members with questions, ideas and feedback. We are always available and keen to hear from our colleagues! 

So far, OzHarvest has delivered over 78 million meals, saving over 26 thousand tons of food from going to landfill and counting!

1.4 Photography and Film  

Occasionally you may have food donors ask if they can film you and your van picking up food from them. This is usually great as it increases our brand awareness and is a way for food donors to be able to share how they support us. However, please keep in mind that we have certain commitments to our partners, which includes restrictions around the OzHarvest brand being associated with their competitors. For this reason, when you get asked to be photographed or filmed please request that the final product is sent to Ashley Killeen via email [Ashley.Killeen@ozharvest.org](mailto:Ashley.Killeen@ozharvest.org) or text 0422 273 935 so she can check it is OK from a brand point of view.  

1.5 Volunteers, VIP's and Media 

On occasion, you will be asked to take volunteers or VIP’s out for a ride along. They are there to help you but not do your job. Please be mindful of actions and language you use, remember you are the face of the organisation. 

Media ride along will usually be arranged in advance. If you are required to say or do anything, you will be fully briefed prior. 

When driving be mindful of distractions. If a passenger is somehow causing hazardous distractions, it is up to the driver to politely manage the situation and refocus on the task at hand.   

1.6 Food is Free 

OzHarvest do not distribute food direct to the public, we only deliver to organisations or groups that provided assistance to people in need.  

Our service is completely free of charge, and it is a requirement that no fee be charged or conditions be placed on people accessing OzHarvest food. You should immediately report to your Logistics team any concerns over our agencies charging fees to their clients.  

2. Food Rescue Measure of success  

2.1 Quality, Quantity, Consistency are the key performance indicators \(KPI\) that underpin our work as a food rescue team. As a driver, you play a key role in working towards these targets, so it is important you have a good understanding of each measure.  

Quality: Healthy food is a direct link to nourishing our local community. We record categories of food and measure the balance of these categories to show nutritional content of the rescued food. 

Quantity: The most obvious measure of food rescue is the volume rescued. We measure the quantity of kgs rescued, converted into charitable donations of meals.  

Consistency: Consistent donations allow for effective and efficient logistics, resulting in more quality food being rescued and enabling charities to better plan on food received. We measure the percentage of pre-booked donations that successfully donate food.    

2.2 REPORTING 

OzHarvest logistics team in Australia receive a month end report from head office showing results on each of these measures. This data is also offered to all our major food donation partners. Reports like this are shared in driver meetings, and other communication methods described later, however drivers are encouraged to seek out this information at any time via their Logistics Manager.

3. Motor Vehicle Policy 

OzHarvest provides and maintains a vehicle fleet with a range of vehicle types appropriate to the needs of OzHarvest’s operations. These vehicles form the vehicle pool and are available for use by authorised users for travel required for OzHarvest business activities.  

The purpose of this policy is to first and foremost ensure the safety of our family members, contractors and the members of the public. To that end, this policy provides information to all OzHarvest employees, contractors and volunteers so that they understand their responsibilities when operating OzHarvest motor vehicles or vehicles hired for OzHarvest business purposes. 

3.1 Driving for OzHarvest 

Our Drivers are utmost valued members of our family as they are the face of the organisation in the front line of our Operations. They are our ambassadors, dealing with food donors and food relief organisations on a daily basis, developing, managing and improving relationships and helping spread the word about the importance of Food Rescue. While reducing the amount of good food going to landfills, we proudly feed and nourish the most vulnerable in our community. Welcome and thank you for being a part of it!  

3.2 Approved Drivers 

The driver of an OzHarvest vehicle must be an employee, contractor or duly assigned volunteer of OzHarvest and the employee, contractor or volunteer must be fully licenced to drive the classification of the vehicle. 

A photocopy of each driver’s current licence is to be provided. This will be kept as a record on the individuals’ file. Employees, contractors or volunteers are to notify OzHarvest management immediately of any change to the status or validity of the licence. 

If a driver is unfit to drive because of ill health, suspensions or cancellation of licence, the driver must advise their OzHarvest manager and their Head of Business or CFO \(for Business Services\).  OzHarvest reserves the right to dismiss an employee or contractor who loses his or her driver’s licence if the job requires the use of a vehicle and if no other arrangements are available. 

Only authorised drivers are permitted to drive OzHarvest fleet vehicles. All authorised drivers MUST be an OzHarvest staff member or volunteer and have acknowledged/completed/supplied: 

* Drivers of company or hired company vehicles must be authorised to do so and must hold a current driver’s license to drive the classification of the vehicle. 
* Print out for last 5 year driving history – available from your Roads & Traffic authority centre; 
* Police Check and Work with Children Check;  
* Undergone OzHarvest driver training. 
* Drivers are fully responsible for the vehicle while it is in their charge. 
* Traffic regulations and bylaws must be observed at all times. 
* All traffic and parking violations are the responsibility of the authorised driver of the vehicle. 
* Vehicles must be driven at safe speeds according to the road conditions and within speed limits at all times. 
* Every courtesy must be shown to other road users and pedestrians. 
* Company vehicles are serviced at the manufacturer’s recommended intervals and maintained in a roadworthy condition. However, drivers are required to check for obvious defects and report these immediately. 
* Drivers are required to regularly check petrol, tyre pressure and windscreen washer supply. 
* Unattended vehicles must be securely locked. 

Except in cases of a genuine emergency, the authorised driver will not permit any other person who is not an authorised driver to drive the vehicle. Any emergency that requires another person to drive the vehicle should be reported to OzHarvest Operations as soon as possible. 

3.3 Use of OzHarvest Vehicle 

OzHarvest vehicles are to be used for OzHarvest business purposes only.  They are not to be driven to and from a driver’s residence or accommodation unless there is a business efficiency and cost benefit in doing so which has been pre-approved by the Head of Operations.  

3.4 Mobile Phones 

Mobile phone use without hands free equipment during operation of any motor vehicle is illegal. While your phone can only be used if a hands free kit is fitted, for safety reasons, this is discouraged. Where the technology is in place all OzHarvest owned phones should be connected via Bluetooth to the vehicle. If you are not connected via Bluetooth you are required to either not answer the phone, return the call when able to do so, or find a safe place to pull to the road side to answer the phone. Any fines incurred due to using a mobile phone while driving is the responsibility of the driver.  

No connecting Personal phones to OzHarvest Vans. 

3.5 Care of an OzHarvest Vehicle 

The driver of each vehicle is responsible for the basic maintenance of that vehicle. Basic maintenance should include, as a minimum, monitoring and replenishing vital fluids and lubricants: 

* Fuel; 
* Engine Oil; 
* Coolant; 
* Washer Fluids; 
* Tyre pressure should also be monitored. 

The driver is expected to keep the inside and outside of the vehicle clean and presentable at all times.  No alterations, additions or modifications are to be made to vehicles without approval. 

It is the driver’s responsibility to bring to OzHarvest’s immediate attention any fault that could render the vehicle unsafe or un-roadworthy. Vehicles must not be driven when unsafe, un-roadworthy or in a condition that is likely to cause damage to the vehicle. OzHarvest management will notify when a service is due and this will be arranged as soon as possible. 

3.6 Servicing and Maintenance  

It is the responsibility of the OzHarvest Logistics team to ensure that company motor vehicles have all routine servicing carried out at the frequencies listed in the vehicle maintenance manual located in the glove box. OzHarvest will aim to service all vehicles to the manufacturers recommended intervals. It is the driver’s responsibility to advise every Monday the Odometer Reading and when the next service is due via WhatsApp.  

If a vehicle requires repairs or mechanical check while on the road the Logistics team will notify the driver and they must make all efforts to take the vehicle as scheduled to OzHarvest preferred mechanic / repairer.  

It is the driver’s responsibility to check tyres, oil and water as per the Pre Start Checklist and advise of any irregularities to the Logistics team. 

It is the driver’s responsibility to ensure the vehicle is swept out and mopped each night \(cab & rear\). All spills need to be cleaned up. The vehicles are to be washed as per the “back of van wash” procedure \(See appendix 2\) daily and, once a week, be taken through car wash as directed by Operations. 

3.7 Fuel Charge Cards 

All vehicle key rings have a BP fleet card attached. The vehicle must be fuelled each day prior to returning to the office, or filled as per your local office arrangements \(3/4 full, enough for next shift etc\) Speak with your logictics manager for local details.   

* When paying for fuel enter the correct odometer reading then enter the pin number. 
* Always check that you are using the correct fuel when filling the van \(Do not put Diesel in a petrol engine or petrol into a diesel engine\) If this occurs you will be expected to pay for the repairs, as per the guidelines in section 3.13 Damage to Vehicle and Insurance Excess Payments.  
* Fuel Charge cards are to be used for the purchase of fuel only. No miscellaneous purchases are permitted on these cards. 

3.8 Odometer Readings 

In order to keep accurate records of our motor vehicle fleet it is important that all drivers provide up to date mileage information as requested at the start of week. 

3.9 Inspections 

Drivers are responsible for the condition and safe operation of their assigned vehicles. OzHarvest requires drivers to check their vehicles for possible defects and report them according to policy. 

The family member or contractor responsible for the vehicle will inspect the vehicle daily using the Pre Start  

Checklist supplied with the vehicle, and forward the report to their Logistics Coordinator or Manager.  More frequent inspections and reports may be required based on heavy use. 

3.10 Traffic Offences  

Before the commencement of employment, a Driver’s Declaration is required to be signed and sent to OzHarvest Management.  

Any traffic violation or offence of any sort committed by an employee or contractor will remain the sole responsibility of that employee or contractor.  OzHarvest will not be liable for any fines or penalties as a result of vehicle use by its employees or contractors at any time. The driver of any vehicle who has knowledge of a formal notice of an offence must notify OzHarvest immediately.

All drivers are expected to report all accidents, incidents or injuries to the Logistics Day Controller and Logistics Coordinator immediately after they happen or as soon as it is safe to do so. All motor vehicle incidents or injuries at the workplace require an Incident/accident report to be completed. Incident/accident forms can be found with the Logistics Team. Please take photos of all incidents/accidents where possible and safe to do so. It will help in the reporting process. All OzHarvest mobile phones have cameras.

3.12 Personal property & Locking vehicle 

OzHarvest will not cover the loss or damage of personal property whilst in company motor vehicles. Please do not leave important or expensive items in the vehicles while unattended. Ensure all items carried in the vehicle are stored safely and out of sight where possible.   

It is the driver’s responsibility to ensure the vehicle is locked and secure when unattended.   

3.13 Damage to Vehicle and Insurance Excess Payments 

If an employee or contractor causes damage to a vehicle through his or her own negligence, then that employee or contractor will be required to pay for the insurance excess for repair of the damage of the vehicle as follows based on any twelve \(12\) month rolling period:   

* For any driver who drives an OzHarvest vehicle for 25 hours or more per week, OzHarvest will pay for the excess costs for the first two \(2\) at fault accidents and drivers will pay excess costs for the third \(3rd\) and more at fault accidents.  
* For any driver who drive less than 25 hours per week, OzHarvest will pay for the excess costs for the first \(1st\) at fault accident and the driver will pay excess costs for the second \(2nd\) and more at fault accidents. 
* For volunteers there will be nil excess costs; however, a volunteer who has two \(2\) at fault accidents will not be allowed to drive an OzHarvest vehicle. 

Failure to comply with the above policies may result in the removal of vehicle usage or disciplinary action including termination of employment in serious circumstances. 

The excess payment current from November 2018 is $500.  

3.14 Breakdowns 

At the first possible opportunity, you should contact the Logistics Team and report if necessary arrangements must be made to complete the day’s collections and deliveries and, if required, to rescue the contents of the vehicle for distribution before they are spoiled.  

Daytime Contact Number: Each state office to update and save as a state version   

Out of Hours/Emergency: Each state office to update and save as a state version  

In the event of a roadside breakdown call the CUSTOM FLEET 1300 139 555 the vehicle registration number. 

At all times contact the operations team first as vehicle breakdowns will disrupt operations.  

3.15 Alcohol, Drugs and the Like 

Any driver who is affected by drugs, prescribed or social, or alcohol must not use an OzHarvest vehicle. No employee or contractor can drive an OzHarvest vehicle with a blood alcohol level above the prescribed limit \(insurance becomes void\), or be under the influence of medication and/or social drugs which may impair performance. 

An employee or contractor who is found to be affected by alcohol or drugs, will pay for any damage to the OzHarvest vehicle, other vehicles, people or property as a result of an accident where that employee or contractor is the driver of an OzHarvest vehicle. 

An employee who is found to have driven under the influence of drugs or alcohol may be dismissed. 

Smoking is not permitted in any OzHarvest vehicle, as per the OzHarvest Smoking policy. At OzHarvest HQ, smoking is only permitted in the designated outside smoking area.

5. Internal Communication Systems and Technology 

5.1 Training 

All drivers complete the following training: 

* OzHarvest driver training programme \(2 volunteer observation days, 3 paid training days\) 
* Online Manual Handling;  
* Online Food Handling;  
* Any in-house training requirements or courses specific to your local OzHarvest office.  

Copies of all certificates are to be given to the Operations Team to be kept on record. Food Handling Certificates need to be updated every 2yrs. 

5.2 Weekly Drivers Meeting 

At OzHarvest, we value the team’s inputs and we do our very best to keep the drivers on the loop of what the organisation is doing inside and outside the realm of Food Rescue.  

Once a week, a 15-30 minute meeting is held at the office in which the drivers get the chance to exchange ideas and discuss concerns directly with the Logistics Team, meet and hear from other departments within the organisation and explore new ways to improve what we do. OzHarvest takes the safety and wellbeing of all staff, volunteers and clients very seriously. There will be time allocated in all meetings for drivers to bring up any safety concerns and/or point out any potential hazards in compliance with WHS requirements.  

5.3  

Crittah \(www.crittah.com.au\) 

Crittah is used as OzHarvest main Logistical Operational System and is loaded to all phones provided by OzHarvest. All drivers are expected to master the software, as all day-to-day operations data must be recorded.  

WhatsApp \(www.whatsapp.com\) 

WhatsApp is the main daily communication tool used in OzHarvest logistics. During the day, the communication between the office logistics team and drivers will usually happen on the Daily Chat page. All communication must be conducted in a professional, respectful manner.  

Email \(@ozharvest.org\) 

You will be assigned to an OzHarvest email address to which all Rostering, Vehicle and Run Allocation and other Internal Communication will be sent to. You will be required to frequently check your emails and respond accordingly.    

Slack \(ww.slack.com\) 

Slack is used nationally to communicate a variety of information to staff. While it is not currently the main communication tool for Logistics teams \(@March18\), all employees are strongly encouraged to log in to keep up to date on internal communications.  

DropBox  

Every OzHarvest phone should be linked to an OzHarvest DropBox account. This is where information regarding individual vehicles is stored \(condition reports, specs, safety info\). Drivers are required to update the information as per training.   

Page Break6. Your role – a day in the van 

6.1 At the start of your shift  

* Punctuality is essential. You’re expected to be at HQ, in uniform with boots on and ready to start at your designated start time;  
* Collect the OzHarvest phone connected to your run, sign in to Crittah and start your shift; 
* Check your Vehicle and Run allocation as per Crittah; 
* Collect the keys for the Vehicle allocated to you; 
* Check in to WhatsApp; 
* Check ALL jobs allocated to you for that day, ensuring that you read the notes provided for instructions; 
* Perform Vehicle Pre-Start Checklist \(as specified below\); 
* Get clearance with Warehouse Manager/Logistics Manager to load the vehicle; 

6.2 Vehicle Prestart Checklist 

To ensure that motor vehicles used by OzHarvest staff and volunteers are clean and maintained in good repair, it is important to protect, monitor and report the condition of vehicles. To achieve this, all drivers are required to follow the procedures below each time they use an OzHarvest vehicle.  

Before beginning your trip, complete a Vehicle Prestart Checklist as follows: 

* Open the drop box app on the phone and find the file for that specific vehicle, or follow local office procedures; 
* Complete a vehicle walk-around looking for dents not listed in drop box; 
* Add to drop box with a photo and caption any additional items / damage that are not included in drop box and report to Logistics Day Controller immediately; 
* Turn ignition on;  
* Check all lights; 
* Check the refrigeration unit is operating correctly; 
* On the \(each state office to specify when\) also check fluids \(oil, water etc.\). 

Please note that all additional damages to what is found on file MUST be reported to the logistics department at the start of the shift, prior to leaving the office for liability reasons.  

6.3 Your Shift 

* Day Shifts at OzHarvest go for 8 hours with a mandatory 30 minutes rest break and Night Shifts go for 4 hours with a mandatory 30 minutes rest break. \(Please note finishing times may vary from time to time without prior notification due to the fluidity of the role, traffic and other reasons\);   
* Communicate with Donors and Agencies in a responsible, professional and respectful manner and establish and manage the relationships as an OzHarvest Ambassador; 
* Report any issues or concerns regarding the vehicle or run to the Logistics Day Controller throughout the shift either via WhatsApp or office phone;  
* Manage the Job Notes, Contacts and other job details on Crittah by identifying changes and/or discrepancies and reporting immediately to the Logistics Day Controller; 
* Complete all tasks allocated to you or if reasonably unable, to report to the Logistics Day Controller with as much notice as possible who’ll come up with a contingency plan and advise you on how to proceed;   
* When all your allocated jobs are completed, you’re required to check with Logistics Day Controller for any Adhoc jobs prior to returning to the office and only return when receive official clearance via WhatsApp. 

6.4 Breaks 

All drivers are required to take the mandatory Rest Break for any shift over 4 hours. This CAN be taken at anytime after 3hrs 3mins from your start time, and MUST be taken after 5hrs 30mins from the start of your. For example, drivers starting at 8pm must take their break at 12:30pm, drivers starting at 9am must go on their break at 1:30pm, etc…  

Speak with your logistics team to discuss best time for taking breaks. Different times may impact the efficiency of local operations.  

6.5 Collections and Drop-offs 

* Please follow the designated route order as displayed in Crittah.  
* Ensure that the quantities collected and dropped off are properly weighed using the weighing machine placed in the van and recorded in Crittah at each location. These weighing machines are an expensive piece of equipment and are to be handled with care. The weighing machines are to be charged at the charging stations at HQ. Any damage or faulty functioning of the weighing machine is to be reported immediately to the Logistics Day Controller. The Logistics Manager or Warehouse Manager will make arrangements to have the weighing machines checked and calibrated on an as needs basis or when serviced 
* All food items that require packing must be correctly labelled and dated prior to loading. 
* Refrigeration temperatures for all vehicles MUST be at or below 5\[Symbol\]C at all times. Be mindful of the amount of time the doors are kept open while loading or unloading. During your scheduled run, you are to monitor the temperature at regular intervals and report any issues or concerns to the Logistics Team.  
* Any food remaining in the vehicle at the end of the shift MUST be checked for quality and placed into the cool room for holding overnight if safe or disposed of if perished. 
* OzHarvest is very mindful of how we dispose of our rubbish. Unpackaged food items MUST be placed in the Organic Bins and all packaging and other items MUST be disposed of mindfully and accordingly in bins provided. See Warehouse Manager to obtain more information if required.   

6.6 Cancelling/Rejecting jobs  

Cancelling a job have repercussions that may affect the relationships between OzHarvest and the companies and persons who rely on our services. Therefore, it is paramount that in case of inevitable cancelation, the driver communicates to the Logistics team who will assist by ensuring that the relationship is preserved.  

The goal at OzHarvest is to rescue and deliver as much food as possible; we understand that sometimes it is logistically impossible. Although the Logistics Day Controller is experienced in all runs and will be mindful of the time and capacity, there are some of the circumstances in which the driver may need to cancel or reject jobs. 

* Breakdown/Accident – including failure of the refrigeration unit. 
* Full vehicle - you don’t have room in your vehicle for an allocated pickup  
* No time - you notice that a specific allocated job will take too much time pushing you into overtime. 
* No Site Access – you cannot access the pickup site, or cannot make contact with the donor/agency. 

Agencies go through a long process to become an OzHarvest Food Recipient and it is absolutely essential to the organisation that a high standard of service is provided. Cancelling a drop off can have huge repercussions to the community and should be avoided at all costs.  

6.7 Packing the vehicles 

Ensure food is stacked safely for transporting in the vehicle. The better it is packed the less chance of a spillage.  

* stack heavier crates on the bottom 
* stack from the front to the rear 
* meat is bottom stacked to avoid contamination

6.9 At the completion of your shift
